tags":["verb"],"has_etymology":true,"sense_count":3},"lanes":{"found":false}},"translations":null,"definition":{"source":"wiktextract","senses":[{"pos":"verb","gloss":"to give up hope, to despair, to be hopeless","examples":[{"text":"الأمل الذي يعطيه الكتاب المقدس يساعدنا أن نتحمَّل مشاكلنا ولا نيأس","english":"The hope given by the Bible helps us to endure our problems and not despair."}]},{"pos":"verb","gloss":"to become barren"},{"pos":"verb","gloss":"to know, to have certainty, to realize or to accept, to come to a realization to know a thing to be so or true","tags":["archaic","dialectal"],"examples":[{"text":"أَفَلَمْ يَيْأَسِ الَّذِينَ آمَنُوا أَنْ لَوْ يَشَاءُ اللَّهُ لَهَدَى النَّاسَ جَمِيعًا","english":"...Do not those who have trusted come to the realization that, if God caused it to be, He could certainly direct aright all people?..."}]}]},"etymology":{"source":"wiktextract","text":"From the same root of a barren woman, to have no hope of conceiving; developing to mean just accepting that this is how things are, knowing that she cannot, to know one cannot succeed, to have no hope of anything other.\nFrom there the sense of to stop hoping, to give up being concerned with, to abandon worrying over, to accept it to be so; a parallel semantic sense can be found in Jewish Palestinian Aramaic, Jewish Literary Aramaic יאּש (yaʾʾēš, “to remove desperate thoughts, to stop one's mind from thinking about”)."},"ipa":null}